CSS Selector (Cascading style sheet):
    It is another way for locating elements on the web page.

Syntax:
    tagname[attribute='attribute_value']
    ex: button[type='submit']

CSS Selector does NOT give an opportunity to locate the element by its text.

Shortcuts for CSS:
    1. Shortcut for ClassName -> "."
    Syntax: tagname.classNameValueAttribute
    ex: input.button

    2.Shortcuts for ID -> "#"
    Syntax: tagname#IDValue
    Ex: input#twotabsearchtextbox

    3. contains() method in CSS:
    * symbol represents contains method
    Syntax: tagname[attribute*='attribute_value']
    ex: input[placeholder*='Email']

    4. starts-with method in CSS:
    ^  (Circumflex) symbol represents starts-with method
    Syntax: tagname[attribute ^='starting_attribute_value']
    ex: input[type^='pass']

    5. ends-with method in CSS:
    $ symbol represents ends-with method
    Syntax: tagname[attribute $='ending_attribute_value']
    ex: img[src$='syntax.png']

Xpath vs CSS:
    CSS cannot  locate the elements by text whereas xpath can.
    No ends-with method in xpath.
    CSS is faster than xpath (finding elements)
    CSS has shortcuts.
    No advanced CSS.
    CSS has more simple syntax than Xpath.

WebElement Commands:
    Consists of several methods where we can perform an action and get the element state on the webpage.

    isEnabled() -> boolean value
    isDisplayed() -> boolean value
    isSelected() -> boolean value
    clear() -> void method (not return anything)
    getText() -> String value
    getAttribute() -> String value
    submit() -> void






